{"text": "parameter \u2206(r, \u03b8) = \u2206(r) ei\u03b8 and \u03bc(r) = \u03bc0h(r), the BdG equations near the vortex core\n\ncan be written in polar coordinates. It can then be shown that19, in the weak pairing phase\n\nand for a vortex with flux quantum hc\n\n2e, the BdG equations near the vortex core admit a\n\nzero energy solution analogous to the Jackiw-Rebbi solution near a mass domain wall as in\n\nthe case of the boundary or the sample edge. The zero energy solution near the vortex core\n\nexists in the orbital angular momentum channel l = 0. More generally, the low-energy BdG\n\nsolutions describing chiral edge modes propagating along the circular edge at r = r0 with\n\nenergy E can be written as,\n\n\u03c7E(r, \u03b8) = eil\u03b8e\u2212\n\nR r\n\nr0 h(r\u2032)dr\u2032\n\n\uf8eb\n\n\uf8ede\u2212i\u03b8/2\n\nei\u03b8/2\n\n\uf8f6\n\n\uf8f8\n\n(31)\n\nwhere l is the orbital angular momentum and E = \u03bc0l\n\nr0\n\n12. If the vortex has an odd number of\n\nflux quantum hc\n\n2e, the BdG wave function must be anti-periodic upon one full rotation around\n\nthe vortex core, \u03b8 \u2192\u03b8 + 2\u03c0. However, since the spinor on the right hand side of Eq. 31 is\n\nalso anti-periodic upon \u03b8 \u2192\u03b8 + 2\u03c0, it follows that l must be an integer (including zero).\n\nThus, a hc\n\n2e vortex (or vortices with flux nhc\n\n2e with n odd) admit a zero energy solution for\n\nl = 0. Conversely, if the flux inside the vortex core is an even multiple of hc\n\n2e, the BdG wave\n\nfunction must be periodic upon \u03b8 \u2192\u03b8 + 2\u03c0. This ensures that l must be a half-odd-integer\n\nand there will be no zero energy mode inside the vortex core even in the weak pairing phase\n\nof 2D px + ipy superconductor. Analogous to the zero mode solution near the boundary, the\n\nwave function of the zero energy solution near a vortex is exponentially localized away from\n\nthe vortex core.", "embedding": [0.023800962, 0.0118739065, 0.021046864, 0.02545227, -0.